The paper addresses the problem of learning in an online setting with features, actions, and rewards, which is a common problem in machine learning and artificial intelligence. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also uses a cost-sensitive classification learner as an oracle, which involves classification and decision-making, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a likely sub-category as well. Additionally, the paper discusses regret, which is a measure of performance in decision-making, making cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions running time, which involves computational complexity, making cs.IT (Information Theory) a possible sub-category as well.
